The '''Church of St George''' ({{lang-bg|<U+0446><U+044A><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0430> <U+201E><U+0421><U+0432><U+0435><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0413><U+0435><U+043E><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438><U+201C>}}, ''tsarkva <U+201E>Sveti Georgi<U+201C>'') is a medieval [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] church in the city of [[Kyustendil]], which lies in southwestern [[Bulgaria]] and is the administrative capital of [[Kyustendil Province]]. The church is located in the Kolusha neighbourhood, which was historically separate from the city. The church was constructed in the 10th<U+2013>11th century and its [[fresco]]es are somewhat later, as the earliest layers were painted in the 11th<U+2013>12th century.

==History==
The Church of St George is dated to the late 10th or early 11th century based on its architectural appearance and mural paintings, which makes it the oldest preserved church in the city.<ref name="museum">{{cite web|url=http://www.kyustendilmuseum.primasoft.bg/bg/mod.php?mod=userpage&menu=380102&page_id=195|title=<U+0421><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0446><U+044A><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0430> <U+201E><U+0421><U+0432>. <U+0413><U+0435><U+043E><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438><U+201D>|publisher=<U+0420><U+0435><U+0433><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D> <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438> <U+043C><U+0443><U+0437><U+0435><U+0439>&nbsp;<U+2014> <U+041A><U+044E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+043D><U+0434><U+0438><U+043B>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref><ref name="holyplaces">{{cite web|url=http://www.holyplaces-kn.com/en/kyustendil/pametnici-na-kulturata/|title=Medieval church <U+201E>St. George<U+201D>|publisher=Holy Places in Kyustendil District|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> It is located in Kyustendil's southwestern part, in the former village of Kolusha, which in 1939 was merged into the city.<ref name="choleva">{{cite book|last=<U+0427><U+043E><U+043B><U+0435><U+0432><U+0430><U+2013><U+0414><U+0438><U+043C><U+0438><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+0410><U+043D><U+043D><U+0430> <U+041C>.|title=<U+0421><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438><U+0449><U+043D><U+0438> <U+0438><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D><U+0430> <U+043E><U+0442> <U+042E><U+0433><U+043E><U+0437><U+0430><U+043F><U+0430><U+0434><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F>: <U+0418><U+0437><U+0441><U+043B><U+0435><U+0434><U+0432><U+0430><U+043D><U+0435>. <U+0420><U+0435><U+0447><U+043D><U+0438><U+043A>|publisher=<U+041F><U+0435><U+043D><U+0441><U+043E><U+0444><U+0442>|location=<U+0421><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+044F>|year=2002|isbn=954-642-168-5|oclc=57603720|language=Bulgarian|page=132}}</ref>

There is a theory that [[List of Bulgarian rulers|Bulgarian emperor]] [[Michael Shishman of Bulgaria|Michael Shishman]] was buried in the Church of St George after he perished in the [[Battle of Velbazhd]] in 1330.<ref name="museum"/><ref name="holyplaces"/> The battle was a [[Serbia]]n victory over the [[Second Bulgarian Empire]] which paved the way for the [[Serbian Empire|short-lived Serbian dominance]] over the [[Balkans]] in the mid-14th century.<ref name="fine">{{cite book| last = Fine, Jr.| first = John Van Antwerp| year = 1994| title = The Late Medieval Balkans| publisher = [[University of Michigan]] Press| location = [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]]| isbn = 978-0-472-08260-5 |page=272}}</ref> However, scholar Bistra Nikolova entirely dismisses this theory as an "erroneous reference in [Bulgarian history] literature".<ref name="nikolova">{{cite book |last=<U+041D><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430> |first=<U+0411><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430> |title=<U+041F><U+0440><U+0430><U+0432><U+043E><U+0441><U+043B><U+0430><U+0432><U+043D><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435> <U+0446><U+044A><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0438> <U+043F><U+0440><U+0435><U+0437> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0442><U+043E> <U+0441><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+0435> IX<U+2013>XIV <U+0432>. |year=2002 |isbn=954-430-762-1 |publisher=<U+0410><U+043A><U+0430><U+0434><U+0435><U+043C><U+0438><U+0447><U+043D><U+043E> <U+0438><U+0437><U+0434><U+0430><U+0442><U+0435><U+043B><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> "<U+041C><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0414><U+0440><U+0438><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432>" |language=Bulgarian |location=<U+0421><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+044F> |page=134 }}</ref>

Despite being located outside Kyustendil at the time, up until the construction of the city's main [[Bulgarian National Revival]]-style church in 1816, the Church of St George served as Kyustendil's [[cathedral]].<ref name="strahilova">{{cite web|url=http://liternet.bg/publish20/d_strahilova/za_niakoi.htm|title=<U+0417><U+0430> <U+043D><U+044F><U+043A><U+043E><U+0438> <U+043E><U+0441><U+043E><U+0431><U+0435><U+043D><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0441><U+044A><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+044F><U+043D><U+0438><U+0435><U+0442><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0446><U+044A><U+0440><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0436><U+0438><U+0432><U+043E><U+043F><U+0438><U+0441> <U+0432> <U+041A><U+044E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+043D><U+0434><U+0438><U+043B> <U+0438> <U+041A><U+044E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+043D><U+0434><U+0438><U+043B><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E> <U+043F><U+0440><U+0435><U+0437> <U+0435><U+043F><U+043E><U+0445><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+043D><U+043E><U+0442><U+043E> <U+0432><U+044A><U+0437><U+0440><U+0430><U+0436><U+0434><U+0430><U+043D><U+0435>|last=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430><U+0445><U+0438><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+0414><U+0435><U+0441><U+0438><U+0441><U+043B><U+0430><U+0432><U+0430>|year=2007|publisher=LiterNet|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> The church suffered some severe damage during the 19th century, the time of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule of Bulgaria; it was mostly destroyed, leaving only the foundations of the arches. It was reconstructed in 1878<U+2013>1880, just after the establishment of the [[Principality of Bulgaria]],<ref name="museum"/><ref name="holyplaces"/> with further restoration in the 2000s.<ref name="evrofinansirane">{{cite web|url=http://www.evrofinansirane.eu/content/view/918/51/|title="<U+0415><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0445><U+0443><U+0431><U+0430><U+0432> <U+043F><U+0440><U+043E><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442> <U+0432><U+0438><U+043D><U+0430><U+0433><U+0438> <U+0438><U+043C><U+0430> <U+0448><U+0430><U+043D><U+0441> <U+0434><U+0430> <U+0431><U+044A><U+0434><U+0435> <U+0440><U+0435><U+0430><U+043B><U+0438><U+0437><U+0438><U+0440><U+0430><U+043D>"|publisher=<U+0415><U+0432><U+0440><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+043D><U+0430><U+043D><U+0441><U+0438><U+0440><U+0430><U+043D><U+0435>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref>

==Architecture and decoration==
The church follows the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] [[cross-in-square]] design and measures {{convert|10|x|8.70|m|ft}}. The dome is [[octagon]]al and features eight bays, four of which contain windows. There is no [[narthex]] and the [[cella]] appears square. A total of six pillars support the church from the inside. Two frame the entrance of the [[altar]], while the remaining four stand below the dome. The church has three [[apse]]s, all of a [[semicircle|semicircular]] design. Materials used for the church's construction were [[brick]]s and [[Mortar (masonry)|mortar]], resulting in interchanging rows of red and white.<ref name="nikolova"/>

The church's interior has preserved a number of medieval frescoes, particularly in the lower reaches of the walls and pillars. The paintings in the altar were done in the 11th<U+2013>12th century, while the decoration of the pillars dates to the 12th century. All inscriptions that accompany the murals are in [[Medieval Greek]]. The altar features the images of four deacons bearing a [[censer]] and [[monstrance]]s as well as two [[bishop]]s who could possibly be identified as [[Basil of Caesarea]] and [[John Chrysostom]]. A number of saints are also depicted inside the church, including [[Elijah|Saint Elijah]], [[Saints Cosmas and Damian]], Saint Hermolaus, [[Saint Pantaleon]], and four unidentified female saints.<ref name="nikolova"/> There are also later works of art in the church. It boasts icons or murals by painter Ivan Dospevski from 1881 as well as works by Mihail Belstoynev.<ref name="strahilova"/>

Due to its architectural and artistic value, the Church of St George has been part of the list of Bulgaria's monuments of cultural of national importance since 1927. With the reorganization of the list in the 1960s, it was included on it both as an architectural and as an artistic monument, in 1968 and 1969 respectively.<ref name="cultmin">{{cite web|url=http://mc.government.bg/images/NPK/KUSTENDIL.pdf|title=<U+0421><U+043F><U+0438><U+0441><U+044A><U+043A> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043F><U+0430><U+043C><U+0435><U+0442><U+043D><U+0438><U+0446><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043A><U+0443><U+043B><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0441> <U+043A><U+0430><U+0442><U+0435><U+0433><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+201C><U+041D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+043D><U+043E> <U+0437><U+043D><U+0430><U+0447><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0435><U+201D> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0442><U+0435><U+0440><U+0438><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+041E><U+0431><U+043B><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442> <U+041A><U+044E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+043D><U+0434><U+0438><U+043B> /<U+043F><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0435><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438> <U+043C><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430>/|publisher=<U+041C><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+0440><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043A><U+0443><U+043B><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0420><U+0435><U+043F><U+0443><U+0431><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> Together with the native house of [[Dimitar Peshev]] and the city art gallery, since 2010 it has been listed as number 26 among the [[100 Tourist Sites of Bulgaria]].<ref name="dobreva">{{cite web|url=http://www.nablyudatel.com/index.php?lastnews=yes&news_id=2708|title=<U+0421><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0446><U+044A><U+0440><U+043A><U+0432><U+0430> <U+201E><U+0421><U+0432><U+0435><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0413><U+0435><U+043E><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438><U+201D> <U+0432><U+043B><U+0435><U+0437><U+0435> <U+0432> <U+0441><U+043F><U+0438><U+0441><U+044A><U+043A><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0442><U+0435> <U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438> <U+043E><U+0431><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442><U+0430>|last=<U+0414><U+043E><U+0431><U+0440><U+0435><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+0420><U+0430><U+0439><U+043A><U+0430>|date=2010-09-23|publisher=<U+041D><U+0430><U+0431><U+043B><U+044E><U+0434><U+0430><U+0442><U+0435><U+043B>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref>

